    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>An Ugly Trail Of Anti-Semitism</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Tanweer Akram says criticism of Israel and call for end of illegitimate occupation of Palestinian West Bank and Gaza should not be equated with anti-Semitism (Apr 27 article on anti-Semitism among Muslims)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Anti-Semitism Is Deepening Among Muslims'' (Arts &amp; Ideas pages, April 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Anti-Semitism Is Deepening Among Muslims'' (Arts &amp; Ideas pages, April 27):</p>
        <p>Criticism of Israel and the call for the end of its illegitimate and immoral occupation of Palestinian West Bank and Gaza should not be equated with anti-Semitism. Those who refuse to condemn Israel's violation of human rights and humanitarian laws are doing a disservice.</p>
        <p>Many progressive scholars, human rights activists and social workers, both in Muslim countries and abroad, including the United States, frequently collaborate and work together with Jewish intellectuals and activists in a spirit of common and universal human values.</p>
        <p>Despite the notorious and vulgar anti-Semitic imagery used by extremists who are often supported by dictatorial regimes and monarchs, the vast majority of Muslims do not engage in anti-Semitic polemics and hatred. Many Muslims have strongly condemned anti-Semitism, discrimination against Jews and all forms of bigotry.</p>
        <p>TANWEER AKRAM  Alexandria, Va., April 27, 2002</p>
      </block>
